---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Projected Phase Space - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Projected Phase Space</h1>
    
    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Projected Phase Space (PPS)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Observational diagnostic / Parameter space</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Coordinates:</th>
          <td>r = R<sub>proj</sub>/R<sub>200</sub>, v = |v<sub>LOS</sub>/sigma|</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key Papers:</th>
          <td>
            Rhee et al. (2017)<br>
            Pasquali et al. (2019)<br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" />
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Related:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="Galaxy Infall Time" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/environmental_quenching" text="Environmental Quenching" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="Galaxy Clusters" />
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>Projected phase space</strong> (PPS) is the two-dimensional parameter space defined by a satellite galaxy's projected cluster-centric distance and line-of-sight velocity relative to its host halo. It is the primary observational diagnostic for estimating <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="galaxy infall times" /> and studying environmental processing in <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="galaxy clusters" /> and <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_groups" text="galaxy groups" /><sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <h2 id="section-0">Definition</h2>
    
    <p>The PPS coordinates are typically defined as<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>r = R<sub>proj</sub> / R<sub>200</sub></strong> - Projected distance from the cluster center, normalized by the host's virial radius.</li>
      <li><strong>v = |v<sub>LOS</sub> / sigma|</strong> - Absolute line-of-sight velocity relative to the cluster mean, normalized by the halo velocity dispersion.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The velocity dispersion sigma is commonly computed using the calibration from Yang et al. (2007)<sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup>: sigma = 397.9 km/s * (M<sub>h</sub> / 10^14 h^-1 Msun)^0.3214 (Eq. 1 in Masson & Parker 2026<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>).</p>

    <h2 id="section-1">Physical Interpretation</h2>
    
    <p>Position in PPS correlates with orbital history<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Lower-left region (small r, small v):</strong> Galaxies that have been satellites for a long time and have settled deep within the potential well. These typically have the longest <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall times" />.</li>
      <li><strong>Upper-right region (large r, large v):</strong> Recently accreted galaxies on their first infall passage or interlopers. These have the shortest infall times (or are not yet true satellites).</li>
      <li><strong>Intermediate regions:</strong> Mix of orbital phases; galaxies may be on first passage, backsplash orbits, or multiple pericenter passages.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-2">Projection Effects and Interlopers</h2>
    
    <p>PPS is a 2D projection of the full 6D phase space, which introduces degeneracies<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Interloper contamination:</strong> Galaxies beyond 3R<sub>200</sub> in 3D can project within 3R<sub>200</sub> in PPS. Masson & Parker (2026) find interloper fractions exceeding 60% at r &gt; 2 and high velocities, but below 10% at r &lt; 1 (Section III.4, Fig. 3)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This is consistent with findings by Rhee et al. (2017)<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup> and Dou & Yu (2025)<sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Recommended observational cut:</strong> Restrict analyses to r &lt; 2 where interloper contamination is manageable<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
      <li><strong>Bimodality:</strong> At a given PPS location, the <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall time" /> distribution is often bimodal (early vs. late infallers), meaning a single representative T<sub>inf</sub> value is insufficient<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-3">Calibration Methods</h2>
    
    <p>Cosmological simulations are used to calibrate the mapping from PPS position to infall time:</p>
    
    <h3>Discrete Zone Approach</h3>
    <p>Pasquali et al. (2019)<sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup> and Rhee et al. (2017)<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup> divided PPS into discrete zones and assigned mean T<sub>inf</sub> values per zone. This is simple to apply but introduces edge effects at zone boundaries.</p>

    <h3>Continuous Approach</h3>
    <p><WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" /><sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup> used symbolic regression on IllustrisTNG simulations to derive a continuous analytic formula for T<sub>inf</sub>(r, v, M<sub>*</sub>, z), eliminating edge effects and extending the calibration to 0 &lt; z &lt; 1.</p>

    <h2 id="section-4">Applications</h2>
    <p>PPS analysis has been applied to spectroscopic surveys to study environmental processing:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Kim et al. (2023)<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup> used PPS-based infall times to show a gradual decline of star formation since cluster infall at 0.3 &lt; z &lt; 1.1.</li>
      <li>Sampaio et al. (2021)<sup><a href="#ref7">7</a></sup> and Oxland et al. (2024)<sup><a href="#ref8">8</a></sup> applied PPS calibrations to study quenching timescales in observed clusters.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-5">Open Questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Can additional observables (e.g., color, morphology, gas content) break the degeneracy between early and late infallers at the same PPS position?<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>How do substructure and cluster dynamical state affect PPS-based infall time estimates?</li>
      <li>What is the optimal way to handle interloper contamination in observational samples?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-6">See Also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="Galaxy Infall Time" /> - The quantity estimated from PPS</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/environmental_quenching" text="Environmental Quenching" /> - Mechanisms whose timescales are probed via PPS</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="Galaxy Clusters" /> - Host environments</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" /> - Latest PPS-based infall calibration</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/portal_galaxy_evolution" text="Portal: Galaxy Evolution" /></li>
    </ul>

